{"title":"Multi-Task Fusion via Reinforcement Learning for Long-Term User Satisfaction in Recommender Systems","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"In large-scale recommender ranking, fusing multiple predicted user-feedback signals with fixed or greedily tuned weights fails to personalize by user/context and ignores long-term (session-level) satisfaction.","method":"Formulate session-based multi-task fusion as an MDP where the state encodes user profile and recent interactions and the action is the fusion-weight vector applied to MTL outputs. Design a reward aggregating multiple behaviors (e.g., play time, play integrity, interactions) to capture user stickiness and activeness. Train entirely from logs via a BCQ-based actor-critic: a conditional VAE generates in-distribution candidate weight vectors, a perturbation network refines them, and double critics with clipped double Q-learning evaluate them—constraining OOD actions, reducing extrapolation error, and yielding personalized fusion weights at serving time."},{"problem":"Purely offline batch RL for fusion-weight optimization is constrained by behavior-policy coverage, risking local optima and persistent extrapolation issues in the continuous action space.","method":"Introduce an online exploration module that gathers trajectories with a Mixed Multi-Exploration policy, combining random exploration and Gaussian action-noise around the current target policy’s actions. This enriches coverage with high-value, near-optimal actions while maintaining diversity, and the collected data are fed back into offline training—improving robustness and outperforming random-only exploration."},{"problem":"Evaluating new long-term optimization policies offline is risky because standard OPE can overestimate returns on out-of-distribution state-action pairs, potentially promoting harmful policies to online A/B tests.","method":"Propose a Conservative Offline Policy Estimator that performs fitted Q evaluation augmented with a CQL-style regularizer to penalize Q-values for OOD actions, producing a lower-bound estimate of a policy’s per-session long-term value from held-out logs. This estimator guides offline model selection and aligns with observed online outcomes, filtering policies that would degrade user experience."}]}
